  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "HK",
    "text": "Well, my children, I am a little bit disappointed that they are not so much interested in the past. They ask me. But it's not what should be. [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] I think in the future, they will learn a little bit more, for it's important that we remember those things. Right now, I'm retired. And I'm working for the Holocaust Memorial in Miami Beach as a volunteer. I go to schools and churches. And we talk. They give my experience from the Holocaust. I work with the Documentation Center. And also, I made the first reunion of the St. Louis, which was done in 1989. We had quite few of survivors here. It was very successful. Last year, I made the documentary with the television crew from Canada and France. They took me back to Europe, to Germany, and to my parents. And in here in Miami Beach, we were about 12 people. And it will be shown-- it was shown already in Germany, France, and some other countries.",
